column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There was a large increase in stock numbers today doubling last weeks offering with reasonably even volumes of local and pastoral cattle. Large drafts of local and pastoral weaner and yearlings were yarded along with good supplies of grown steers, heifers and prime cows showing heavy weights and finish. The buyer Gallery was notably full with the regulars all present while the feeder and restocker sector had several seasonal buyers bidding on selected lines resulting in price gains on younger cattle.
  Vealer steers sold well and gained 50/60c selling from 250c to 380c while vealer heifers had a wider price spread with lighter frames starting at 162c to 254c and with more cover up to 310c/kg. Yearling steers in store condition sold from 224c to 340c and heavier steers up to 360c/kg. Yearling heifers also gained around 50c with plainer heifers selling from 154c to 230c and in better condition from 240c to a top of 320c/kg.
Pastoral steer calves lifted slightly to return 200c to 280c and big lines of Droughtmaster heifers were making 158c to 218c while plain shorthorn types were hard to sell starting from 50c to 150c/kg.
Grown steers remain equal selling from 218c to 300c and grown heifers from 218c to 282c/kg.
The cow market was also firm with Light cows returning 60c to 160c while medium cows made 150c to 208c and heavy cows topped at 232c/kg
Shipping bulls sold to a top of 260c and slaughter bulls sold from 182c to 230c/kg
Market reporter Terry Birkin.
